1540","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England":"Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England","Risby, Suffolk, England":"Risby, Suffolk, England","Saffron Waldon, Essex, England":"Essex, England","England":"England","Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1520–1600":"1520–1600","1525–1600":"1525–1600","1540–1600":"1540–1600","1505–1542":"1505–1542","1500–1542":"1500–1542","1571":"1571","25 December 1519":"25 December 1519","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1525":"1525","1600":"1600","30 January 1539":"30 January 1539","1500":"1500","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1542":"1542","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England":"Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England","Risby, Suffolk, England":"Risby, Suffolk, England","Saffron Waldon, Essex, England":"Essex, England","England":"England","Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hollis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Midlands): topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) holly or holly trees’, from Middle English <i>holi(e)</i>, <i>holin</i> (Old English <i>holegn</i>, <i>holen</i>). Compare   Hollen   and   Holley   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Holley","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>hol</i> ‘hollow’ + <i>eie</i>, <i>egh(e)</i> ‘eye’ (Old English <i>hol</i> + <i>ēage</i>), perhaps a nickname for someone with a missing eye.","topographic name for someone who lived by a ‘clearing in a hollow’, from Middle English <i>hol</i> ‘hollow’ + <i>lei(e)</i> ‘woodland clearing’."]},{"name":"Hollins","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hollins (Staffordshire, Lancashire, Yorkshire), or else a topographic name from the plural of Middle English <i>holin</i> ‘holly’ (see   Hollis  )."]},{"name":"Holm","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Lars, Anders, Thor, Holger, Nels, Nils, Sven, Helmer, Lennart, Niels, Vibeke.","English, Scottish, German, and Scandinavian: topographic name for someone who lived on an island, in particular a piece of slightly raised land lying in a fen or partly surrounded by streams, from Middle English, Middle Low German <i>holm</i>, Old Norse <i>holmr</i>, or else a habitational name from a place called with this element. The Swedish name is often ornamental.","English: topographic name for someone who lived where holly grew, from Middle English <i>holm</i>, a divergent development of Old English <i>hole(g)n</i> ‘holly (tree)’; or, especially in southern England, a habitational name from any of the places such as East and West Holme (Dorset) or Holne (Devon). Compare   Hollis  ."]},{"name":"Hollen","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a holly tree, from Middle English <i>holin</i> ‘holly’ (Old English <i>holegn</i>). Compare   Hollis  .","Dutch: patronymic from   Holle   3."]},{"name":"Hollings","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Hollis  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":29,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":38,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":49,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":51,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":65,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":67,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Hollis was born in 1520, in Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England, his father, John Hollis, was 15 and his mother, Elizabeth C Jones, was 20. He married Ursala Cooper on 30 January 1539, in Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1600, in Risby, Suffolk, England, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1520–1600":"1520–1600","1525–1600":"1525–1600","1540–1600":"1540–1600","1505–1542":"1505–1542","1500–1542":"1500–1542","1571":"1571","25 December 1519":"25. detsember 1519","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1525":"1525","1600":"1600","30 January 1539":"30. jaanuar 1539","1500":"1500","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1542":"1542","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England":"Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England","Risby, Suffolk, England":"Risby, Suffolk, England","Saffron Waldon, Essex, England":"Essex, England","England":"England","Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1520–1600":"1520–1600","1525–1600":"1525–1600","1540–1600":"1540–1600","1505–1542":"1505–1542","1500–1542":"1500–1542","1571":"1571","25 December 1519":"25. joulukuuta 1519","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1525":"1525","1600":"1600","30 January 1539":"30. tammikuuta 1539","1500":"1500","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1542":"1542","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England":"Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England","Risby, Suffolk, 